24. Accented monosyllables, ending in a long vowel or a diphthong, are merely shortened before a following short vowel or h, cf. qu? homo (305), ont> eius (430), εἴ eris (677), τὲ honestet (693). So, too, accented monosyllables ending in ‘m are not elided; cf. rem ((901 (842), mim 090 (25). The shortening of 0 111 such a compound as introierit (10) is similar. This is called semi-hiatus.

25. HIATUS. — Aside from the cases just given, hiatus is very common in Plautus. It occurs (1) after interjections,

(2) where there is a change of speakers,

(3) where there is a distinct elocutionary pause in the midst of a speech3

(4) in the middle of a long verse, which is thus treated as if made up of two independent verses3

(5) in certain cases which cannot well be classified. In some of these the text is probably corrupt.
